This project focuses on performing Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on a phishing website detection dataset. The objective was to understand the dataset structure, identify patterns and relationships among features, detect outliers and anomalies, analyze distributions, and generate actionable insights for future machine learning applications.

Tools & Technologies
Python
Pandas
NumPy
Matplotlib
Seaborn
Jupyter Notebook
Project Tasks
Data Understanding and Exploration
Descriptive Statistical Analysis
Missing Value Analysis
Duplicate Record Detection
Distribution Analysis
Skewness Analysis
Outlier Detection using Boxplots
Correlation Analysis
Heatmap Visualization
Pair Plot Analysis
Class Imbalance Analysis
Insights and Recommendations
Key Findings
The dataset contains 11,430 website records and 89 features.
No missing values or duplicate records were found.
The target variable is perfectly balanced between phishing and legitimate websites.
Several URL-based features exhibit positive skewness and significant outliers.
Correlation analysis revealed both independent and highly correlated features.
URL structure characteristics play an important role in phishing website identification.


The EDA process provided valuable insights into phishing website characteristics and confirmed that the dataset is clean, balanced, and suitable for machine learning classification tasks. The findings can support the development of effective phishing website detection models.

